ğŸŒ Day 4 Lab: Allocating an Elastic IP Address
ğŸ“– Lab Explanation
Today, we're allocating an Elastic IP Address - a static, public IPv4 address designed for dynamic cloud computing. Unlike regular public IPs that change when you stop/start instances, Elastic IPs remain constant.

ğŸ” Key Terms Defined
Elastic IP (EIP)
What: A static, public IPv4 address that you can allocate to your AWS account

Purpose: Provides a consistent public IP address that doesn't change

Key Feature: Can be remapped between different EC2 instances

Public IP vs Elastic IP
Public IP: Dynamic, changes when instance stops/starts

Elastic IP: Static, persists until you release it

IP Address Allocation
What: The process of reserving an IP address from AWS's pool

Scope: Regional - allocated to a specific AWS region

ğŸš€ Benefits & Why We Use Elastic IPs
ğŸ”§ Technical Advantages
Static Addressing - consistent IP for DNS records, firewalls, etc.

High Availability - quickly remap to backup instances during failures

No DNS Propagation - immediate failover without DNS changes

ğŸ’¡ Practical Benefits
Service Continuity - maintain same IP even if instance changes

SSL Certificates - required for SSL/TLS certificates that bind to IP

Whitelisting - easy firewall/security group configuration

ğŸ¯ Use Cases
Web Servers - consistent public facing IP

VPN Servers - static IP for remote access

Database Access - whitelisted IP for external connections

Disaster Recovery - quick failover to backup systems

âš ï¸ Important Considerations
Cost: Free when attached to running instance, charges apply when unused

Limit: 5 Elastic IPs per region by default (can be increased)

Association: Must be associated with an EC2 instance or other resource

ğŸ› ï¸ Step-by-Step Solution
Method: AWS Management Console
Login to AWS Console

bash
# Use the provided credentials:
URL: https://386532143645.signin.aws.amazon.com/console?region=us-east-1
Username: kk_labs_user_244282
Password: 6MMFt@4tPYjR
Region: us-east-1 (VERIFY THIS!)
Navigate to EC2 Service

Go to Services â†’ EC2

In left sidebar, find "Network & Security" â†’ "Elastic IPs"

Allocate Elastic IP Address

Click "Allocate Elastic IP address"

Network border group: Keep default (us-east-1)

Public IPv4 address pool: Amazon's pool (default)

Tags (Optional but recommended):

Key: Name

Value: nautilus-eip

Click "Allocate"

Verify Allocation

You should see the new Elastic IP in the list

Note the allocated IP address (e.g., 54.210.132.105)

Status should show as "available"

Add Name Tag (if not done during creation)

Select the Elastic IP

Click "Actions" â†’ "Add/edit tags"

Add tag: Key=Name, Value=nautilus-eip

Click "Save"

ğŸ“‹ What We Created
Resource: Elastic IP Address

Name: nautilus-eip

Status: Available (not yet associated with any instance)

Scope: us-east-1 region

ğŸ”§ Next Steps
